The corresponding recital for Article 24 GDPR (Responsibility of the controller) can be found in Recital 78 of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).

Recital 78 states:

"The controller should be encouraged to implement data protection by design and data protection by default in an effective manner. The controller should be responsible for, and be able to demonstrate compliance with, paragraph 1. This accountability obligation applies in particular to:

(a) the determination of the purposes and means of the processing;

(b) ensuring, through internal resources or through effective cooperation and consultation with the data protection officer, that the controller’s core processes in relation to the rights and obligations of the controller under this Regulation are complied with, in particular as regards the rights to information, objection, erasure and data breach notification;

(c) making and keeping records of processing activities under Article 30;

(d) implementing appropriate technical and organisational measures, such as those referred to in Article 25(1), in particular for ensuring the security of the processing;

(e) fulfilling the duties to cooperate and consult with the supervisory authority pursuant to Articles 31 and 32, in particular in order to demonstrate compliance with this Regulation;

(f) making arrangements for the exercise of data subjects’ rights;

(g) ensuring that, by default, only personal data which are necessary for each specific purpose of the processing are processed;

(h) taking into account the nature, scope, context and purposes of the processing, as well as the risks of varying likelihood and severity for rights and freedoms of natural persons, implementing appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure and to be able to demonstrate that the processing is performed in accordance with this Regulation;

(i) implementing procedures for periodic reviews of policies and practices to ensure that a data protection by design approach is advanced over time;

(j) appointing a data protection officer in accordance with Article 37, where required;

(k) ensuring in an explicit and accessible form, clear and simple language, that the information provided under Articles 13 and 14 and any communication using a layered approach, is easily accessible and easy to understand;

(l) where required under Article 14(2), providing the information to the data subject in writing, or where otherwise requested by the data subject, by electronic means based on request by the data subject and where the data subject does not provide an address;

(m) where the personal data are processed for more than one purpose, indicating in the information provided under Articles 13 and 14, the legal basis for each purpose and, if the legal basis is severalfold, specifying the purposes for which the personal data are processed;

(n) where the personal data are collected from the data subject, providing, in addition to the information referred to in points (a) to (m), the following information:

(i) the purposes of the processing for which the personal data are intended as well as the legal basis for the processing;

(ii) where the processing is based on point (f) of Article 6(1), the legitimate interests pursued by the controller or by a third party;

(iii) the recipients or categories of recipients of the personal data, if any;

(iv) where applicable, the fact that the controller intends to transfer personal data to a third country or international organisation and the existence or absence of an adequacy decision by the Commission, or in the case of transfers referred to in Article 46 or 47, or the second subparagraph of Article 49(1), reference to the appropriate or suitable safeguards and the means by which to obtain a copy of them or where they have been made available;

(v) the period for which the personal data will be stored, or if that is not possible, the criteria used to determine that period;

(vi) the existence of the right to request from the controller access to and rectification or erasure of personal data or restriction of processing concerning the data subject or to object to processing as well as the right to data portability;

(vii) where the processing is based on point (a) of Article 6(1) or point (a) of Article 9(2), the existence of the right to withdraw consent at any time, without affecting the lawfulness of processing based on consent before its withdrawal;

(viii) the right to lodge a complaint with a supervisory authority;

(ix) whether the provision of personal data is a statutory or contractual requirement, or a requirement necessary to enter into a contract, as well as whether the data subject is obliged to provide the personal data and of the possible consequences of failure to provide such data;

(x) the existence of automated decision-making, including profiling, referred to in Article 22(1) and (4) and, at least in those cases, meaningful information about the logic involved, as well as the significance and the envisaged consequences of such processing for the data subject."

The corresponding recital for Article 38 GDPR (Position of the data protection officer) is Recital 97 of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR). Here it is:

Recital 97:

"The data protection officer should be in a position to fulfil the tasks referred to in Article 39(1) and (2) and to have due regard to the risk associated with the processing and the nature of the controller or processor. The data protection officer should have at least the following minimum guarantees:

(a) the post of the data protection officer should have a proper and regularly reviewed status within the structure of the controller or processor;

(b) the data protection officer should report directly to the highest level of management of the controller or processor;

(c) the data protection officer should be involved, in a timely manner, in all issues which relate to the protection of personal data;

(d) the data protection officer should not carry out any other tasks which could result in a conflict of interest;

(e) the data protection officer should have appropriate resources and access to continuous training by virtue of his or her professional qualities;

(f) the data protection officer should not be dismissed or penalised by the controller or the processor for having carried out his or her tasks."

The corresponding recital(s) for Article 50 GDPR (International cooperation for the protection of personal data) can be found in Recitals 101-103 of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR). Here they are:

101. The Union's data protection rules should apply to the processing of personal data by the Member States' public authorities and bodies, as well as by natural or legal persons in the context of the activities of the State, including public authorities and bodies, regardless of whether they are governed by private or public law.

102. The Union and the Member States should establish, in accordance with the principle of conferral and based on reciprocity, a system of cooperation and mutual assistance in the field of data protection between the supervisory authorities of the Member States and the European Data Protection Supervisor, as well as with the supervisory authorities of third countries, in order to ensure the consistent application and enforcement of this Regulation.

103. The system of cooperation and mutual assistance between supervisory authorities should be based on the following principles:

(a) the principle of solidarity and mutual assistance, according to which supervisory authorities should help each other in their respective tasks;

(b) the principle of one-stop-shop, according to which a supervisory authority should act as a single contact point for data controllers or processors established in different Member States, and should cooperate with the supervisory authorities concerned, especially in cases of cross-border processing activities;

(c) the principle of consistency, according to which the lead supervisory authority should ensure the consistent application of this Regulation throughout the Union, especially as regards the exercise of the derogation and the restriction of the data subject's rights, the certification mechanism, and the use of codes of conduct and of data protection seals and marks;

(d) the principle of transparency, according to which the supervisory authorities should inform each other and the data subjects about the measures taken in the context of the system of cooperation and mutual assistance;

(e) the principle of prior involvement of the data subject, according to which the data subject should be informed and have the opportunity to challenge the decisions addressed to the data controller or processor concerned.
